<TITLE> Japan's imperial couple should cut duties:govt </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 TOKYO, Feb 25 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Japan's ageing Emperor Akihito and his wife Empress Michiko should cut back their schedule of official duties because of their health problems, the government's top spokesman said on Monday. The couple's elder son, Crown Prince Naruhito, said over the weekend he believed his parents should have more time to rest. A palace doctor said the 74-year-old emperor could develop osteoporosis because his bone density dropped as a result of treatment for prostate cancer, while Empress Michiko, 73, suffered from bouts of dizziness. "I personally think it is important for their hard work to be gradually cut and for their schedules to be made lighter," Chief Cabinet Secretary Nobutaka Machimura told a news conference. "The Imperial Household Agency will probably take this into consideration when planning their schedules, but I hope that they do so fully," he added, recalling one regional trip in which the couple had hardly any time to rest, from morning until night. The emperor needed to exercise more to overcome his new condition, although there was no recurrence of the cancer for which Akihito underwent surgery five years ago, the doctor said. An Imperial Household Agency official said in a statement the emperor's schedule would need to be revised to allow time for such activities. Naruhito, speaking at a news conference to mark his 48th birthday on Saturday, also sought an easier time for his parents. "I think it is necessary for those around them to consider making more time for them to rest and take it easy," he said. Naruhito's wife, Crown Prince Masako, has been criticised by some tabloid magazines, who have said she spends too much time with friends and family and not enough on official duti
